	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>kevtris</b> [ Tue Jul 05, 2011 9:03 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Help with modded NES, Nintoaster</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Canite wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I think this would be the most appropriate section to put this in..<br /><br />&lt;snip&gt;<br /><br />to this I could find, would be that there was a gounding problem, specifically with the 13v DC from the AC adaptor and 5v DC from the 7805 being grounded to the same spot (the NES board). So, first I moved all of the ground wires closer to each other, as well as tried to seperate the gound from the AC adaptor, but in the process I broke one of the <br /><br />&lt;snip&gt;<br /><br />when I had it working with the buzzing noise, but it only gives a blank screen now. I honestly can not figure out what is wrong. Could the short in the connections have fried the board and/or the Game Genie connector?  And is there any way to test or see if any component is broken?</div>
<br />
<br />Did you power it up, while the ground to the 7805 was lifted?  If so, unregulated 13V probably went into the board and popped some chips.  Without a ground, the 7805 will not regulate, and acts as a fancy wire, basically.  
<br />
<br />Shorting stuff on the 72 pin connector probably isn't going to hurt anything- sure it won't work but if you break the short it's going to work again.  
<br />
<br />One time I blew up an NES because I had unscrewed that little PCB with the power/reset switches on it, and it was flopping around and happened to hit one of the data lines on the main PCB.  Since the power switch is controlling the rectified DC (around 12-13 volts) this blew up every chip connected to the data bus.  I did manage to fix it, but it required replacing the EPROM, CPU, and 6522 on the copyNES board,  the PPU, the two 74HC368 chips (Controller inputs), and the RAM chip on the main board... basically most of the chips.
<br />
<br />You might be luckier than I was though;  it could still just be a short or open somewhere.
<br />
<br />Next time, you can eliminate the hum by careful grounding:
<br />
<br />Connect the ground from the power adapter, audio/video jacks, and 7805 and video amplifier to the ground on the NES board right where the modulator was.  Connect them all to the SAME point.  Also, how are you providing the power to run the NES?  Are you using a full wave rectifier?  If it's half-wave (i.e. a single diode) then that could cause some hum in an otherwise hum-free circuit.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


