	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>infiniteneslives</b> [ Tue Jul 05, 2011 8:32 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Canite wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The ground was definitely still connected.  Is it easy to tell if any of the chips are damaged?  Everything <em>looks</em> fine.<br /><br />And thanks for the advice on the hum.  I'm just using a newer AC adapter to power the NES, so I'm not sure if it's full wave or half wave.  But I also think a problem with the buzzing was because I hadn't put the metal casing over everything yet, so everything was open.<br /><br />But I'm happy that you're saying I still have hope <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /><br /><br />Edit:<br />Ok, so today I desoldered the Game Genie off of there and cleaned off as much solder as I could left over on the 72 board connections and stuck the original 72-pin connector back on.  With this, I managed to get a glitchy mess of graphics instead of a blank screen every once in while (while positioning the cartridge in different spots).  Does this mean it's not completely busted?  Some of the connections may not be connecting fully because of the left over solder on the board.</div>
<br />
<br />If you're getting something vice the previous nothing it sounds like you're on the right track.  I guess you could say it's not "completely" bused but it depends how you define that...
<br />
<br />Your connections are vital obviously.  Sounds like you've got a mess of connections that needs to be cleaned up.  Just keep checking them and make sure you use a multimeter.  Don't be afraid to pull on connections to ensure they aren't weak.  If their weak enough to pull off or wiggle with a small amount of effort you connection was junk anyways, so don't be afraid to tug to ensure you've got a good connection. 
<br />
<br /> One tip, I highly recommend using solder flux in ADDITION to what's already most likely in your solder.  I use a pen type applicator that I really like.  This is something that is commonly neglected and people (including myself at one point) don't understand why it's so hard to make a good solder joint, cleanliness is next to godliness, and flux is one of the best cleaners available to you. 
<br />
<br />Now have fun with those 72 pins...

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


